anizations harness the new media revolution to create powerful global networks to promote common causes, transcending the state and breaking its exclusive control over information.In this book, Nachman Shai examines the case of Israel, a liberal democratic state faced with an incessant stream of diverse, low-intensity threats. Shai discusses the military, political, economic, legal, and public diplomacy fronts of the second intifada (2000–2005) and how Israel deliberated its response in an environment where the state is only one of the players in a global arena in which individuals, nongovernmental organizations, and international news corporations all operate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aArab-Israeli conflictxMass media and the conflict. 0aMass media and international relationszIsrael. 0aMass media and public opinionzIsrael. 0aMass media and warzIsrael. 4aArea Studies : Israel Studies. 4aCommunication : Political Communication. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Mass Media. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Studies. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2018z978311149142440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846907240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438469072423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438469072/original  a978-3-11-149142-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles